  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "zpigrcle7yweOvlHd7oU5ajfa0A=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Why a mesh of per-user feeds is the only option\n\nSwarm enforces a hard constraint at the protocol level: **only the owner can write to their own feed**. There is no shared multi-writer feed primitive. This rules out the naive \"one collaborative feed everyone appends to\" data model.\n\nCollaboration therefore must be structured as a **mesh of per-user feeds that everyone reads**. Each collaborator owns and writes their own set of topics; every other collaborator subscribes to and pulls from those peer-owned feeds.\n\nConcretely, each collaborator gets their own ACT-protected feeds:\n\n```\nTopic: ph:v2:collab:<collabId>:ops:<driveId>         (drive-level ops)\n       ph:v2:collab:<collabId>:ops:<driveId>:<docId> (doc-level ops)\nOwner: each collaborator owns their own topic(s)\nACT:   grantees = all participants' Bee node pubkeys\n```\n\nEach collaborator appends their own ops to their own feeds (debounced + batched, same pipeline as the existing SwarmChannel push). On the read side, every participant registers pull sources for every *other* participant's collab feeds. This mesh topology is a direct consequence of the owner-only-write rule and shapes the rest of the design (GSOC pings per peer, cursor-per-peer-source, etc.).",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
    }
  },
